answers.body_markdown:
You need to use a generic type on the enum constant, though Java doesn&#39;t currently allow it and this seems not to change in the future as the [JEPS 301][1] has been closed and withdrawn.

Here is a full discussion: https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8170351

**Verbose workaround:**

You can create a wrapper for your animal `BiFunction` that makes a decision based on casting whether the wrapped `BiFunction` shall be used for evaluation or a default value (`null` makes sense in this context as long as `Boolean` is used to distinguish from `false` returned from an Animal-specific implementation) is returned directly.

```java
class AnimalBiFunction&lt;T extends Animal&gt; implements BiFunction&lt;T, AnimalDetails, Boolean&gt; {

	private final Class&lt;T&gt; type;
	private final BiFunction&lt;T, AnimalDetails, Boolean&gt; delegate;

	// all-args constructor

	@Override
	public Boolean apply(T t, AnimalDetails details) {
		try {
			return delegate.apply(type.cast(t), details);
		} catch (ClassCastException ignore) {}
		return null; // default value
	}
}
```

The trick is that the generic types are allowed for the scope of the individual methods or constructor in the `enum`, although the `enum` itself cannot be generic. Just wrap the type-specific function into the wrapper. For easy usage, I also recommend `AnimalClass` implementing `BiFunction&lt;Animal, AnimalDetails, Boolean&gt;` itself and delegating the call to the encapsulated function.

```java
enum AnimalTypes implements BiFunction&lt;Animal, AnimalDetails, Boolean&gt; {

    CAN_BARK(new AnimalBiFunction&lt;&gt;(Dog.class, Dog::canBark)),
	CAN_FLY(new AnimalBiFunction&lt;&gt;(Birds.class, Birds::canFly));

	private final AnimalBiFunction&lt;Animal&gt; delegate;

	@SuppressWarnings(&quot;unchecked&quot;)
	&lt;T extends Animal&gt; AnimalTypes(final AnimalBiFunction&lt;T&gt; delegate) {
		this.delegate = new AnimalBiFunction&lt;&gt;(
				Animal.class,
				(BiFunction&lt;Animal, AnimalDetails, Boolean&gt;) delegate
		);
	}

    @Override
	public Boolean apply(final Animal animal, final AnimalDetails details) {
		return delegate.apply(animal, details);
	}
}
```

Finally, the application is quite straightforward. Here is a minimal sample:

```java
final Birds birds = details -&gt; true;
final Dog dog = details -&gt; true;
final Dog cat = details -&gt; false;  // dumb example, but something to yield false

// Birds
System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_BARK.apply(birds, null));    // null
System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_FLY.apply(birds, null));     // true

// Dog
System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_BARK.apply(dog, null));      // true
System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_FLY.apply(dog, null));       // null

System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_BARK.apply(cat, null));      // false
System.out.println(AnimalTypes.CAN_FLY.apply(cat, null));       // null
```



  [1]: https://openjdk.org/jeps/301

